We recommended that Management:
instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to expedite the reconciliation of all PPE accounts and records with the end in view of preparing and maintaining PPELCs for all PPE accounts and items in the format as prescribed in Annex 9 of the Manual;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer, who agreed to prepare the complete Property Cards in the format as prescribed in Annex 37 of the Manual;
ensure that the Inventory Committee conducts a complete physical count of all PPE, prepares the RPCPPE in the format as prescribed in Annex 49 of the Manual, and submits such to the Audit Team on or before January 31 of each year;
ensure that PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards are reconciled before rendering of the RPCPPE to the Audit Team;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to reclassify various PPE items to their proper accounts, following the proposed adjusting journal entries as presented in Appendix G;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare JEVs, who agreed to reclassify semi-expendable properties from PPE, following the proposed adjusting journal entries:

We recommended and Management agreed to instruct:
the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count of all road networks under their jurisdiction and render the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network in the format as prescribed in Annex C of the Circular;
the Municipal Treasurer to expedite the preparation and/or maintenance of the Report on Local Road Networks and Local Road Network Ledger Cards in the formats as prescribed in Annex A and E of the Circular, ensuring accuracy and completeness of the data to be supplied;
the Municipal Accountant to expedite the preparation and maintenance of the Local Road Network Ledger Cards in the format as prescribed in Annex D of the Circular, ensuring accuracy and completeness of the data to be supplied;
the Municipal Accountant to revise the Notes to the Financial Statement to properly state the total number of kilometers of road networks under the jurisdiction of the Municipality; and
the Municipal Accountant to prepare JEVs to reclassify the Boardwalk asset to the Other Land Improvements account, following the proposed adjusting journal entries:

We recommended and Management agreed to:
submit a reasonable justification to the Audit Team on the non- or partial implementation/ completion of each of these development projects;
submit to the Audit Team copies of technical plans and specifications related to the above-cited projects as proof that these are pre-planned and procurement-and-implementation-ready, for further evaluation;
expedite the implementation and completion of the above-cited projects for the benefit of its constituents;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare a JEV to reclassify the purchase of street lights to the proper inventory account, following the proposed adjusting journal entry:
instruct the Municipal Treasurer to determine the total number of street lights installed by the Municipality as of December 31, 2024 and issue RIS; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to recognize the cost of street lights installed in the Construction in Progress account, following the proposed adjusting journal entry:

We recommended and Management agreed to:
instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare a JEV to capitalize the major repairs, following the proposed adjusting journal entry:
instruct the Municipal Engineer to furnish the Municipal Accountant with the actual historical cost of the replaced parts, including supporting documents and computation, for derecognition thereof;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to determine the carrying amount and prepare a JEV to derecognize such, following the proposed adjusting journal entry:
instruct the Municipal Accountant to determine the new carrying amount of the assets, recompute the depreciation expenses and accumulated depreciation, and prepare a JEV to adjust for any discrepancy;
execute a Deed of Donation to Barangays Lawaan and Cabil-isan for the said repairs on the Daycare Center;
upon execution of the donation of the said repairs, instruct the Municipal Accountant, who agreed to prepare a JEV to reclassify the donation, following the proposed adjusting journal entry:
ensure that subsequent municipal projects involving assets not owned/ controlled by the Municipality be executed with a MOA between the two parties.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
instruct the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Treasurer to:
identify all completed infrastructure projects as of date and determine their dates of completion, supposed defects liability period, and supposed date of final acceptance;
classify them according to building type (Types 1 to 5) and identify whether these are Permanent Structures, Semi-Permanent Structures, or Other Structures; and
immediately initiate steps towards the proper issuance Certificates of Final Acceptance by the Municipal Mayor on: (i) Permanent Structures, for those aged 15 years or below; (ii) Semi-Permanent Structures, for those aged 5 years or below; and (iii) Other Structures, for those aged two years or below;
prepare and submit to the Audit Team the status of the infrastructure assets as of date, including any details on any history of repairs, rehabilitations and renovations for further evaluation
instruct the Municipal Engineer to immediately issue a Certificate of Final Acceptance one year after project completion;
demand from contractors the extension of the validity period or, if already expired, the posting of another surety bond for performance and warranty securities in compliance with the IRR; and
establish internal guidelines in the management of infrastructure projects, taking inspiration from DPWH DO No. 166, series of 2024, among other DPWH issuances. Ensure that controls are in place and working effectively to ascertain that the validity period for performance and warranty securities are sufficient to cover the periods as prescribed in the IRR.

We recommended and Management agreed to initiate steps towards the revision of the Plantilla of personnel, taking into consideration the additional manpower needs of all departments and offices of the Municipality, with emphasis on the following:
filling in of vacancies in the Plantilla, especially the MPDC and the MCR positions;
hiring JO workers only to implement local projects in accordance with Section 77 of RA No. 7160;
creating the required divisions in the MTO, such as the Cash Division, Revenue Division, Administrative Section, IT Unit, and Supplies and Property Division/Unit;
creating and filling in the noted lacking mandatory positions of the Municipal Assessor’s Office in compliance with RA No. 7160 and the MRPAAO; and
creating and filling in the noted lacking statutory positions of the MDRRMO in compliance with RA No. 10121 and NDRRMC-DILG-DBM-CSC JMC No. 2014-1.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
ensure that the BAC prepares the required PMR starting from the first semester of CY 2025 and in the form as prescribed by the GPPB;
ensure that the BAC adopts the APCPI system and prepares the APCPI results for CY 2025 in the form as prescribed by the GPPB;
submit the CY 2025 first and second semester PMRs to the GPPB on or before the deadlines set in GPPB Circular No. 02-2020; and
submit the CY 2025 APCPI results to the GPPB on or before the deadline set in GPPB Circular No. 02-2020.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
submit a written explanation on the noted deficiencies, including the non-implementation of nine GAD PPAs with a total budget of ₱1,350,000.00 for further evaluation;
prepare and submit to the Audit Team for further evaluation a revised CY 2024 GAD AR to fully describe in the Actual Results column the necessary description as required in Annex E of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended;
ensure that the CY 2024 GAD AR is duly received by the PPDO and to the DILG in compliance with Item 4.1.C.5 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended; and
ensure that the CY 2024 GAD AR is submitted to the DILG for posting in the FDPP in compliance with DILG MC No. 2019-149.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor:

as the Local Chief Executive, should have the political will to strictly implement its solid waste management plan and remind the Board of their duties and responsibilities enumerated in Section 12 of R.A. No. 9003;

through SWMB, i) ensure effective and efficient enforcement of environmental ordinances towards the attainment of the objectives of the LGU’s Ten-Year Ecological Solid Waste Management Plan; ii) strictly implement and monitor the segregation of wastes at source and collection, transport and handling of solid waste as required by the provisions of Rule VIII, IX and X of the IRR of R.A. No. 9003; and iii) adopt necessary measures to properly manage and monitor the operation of its temporary open dumpsite to mitigate the possible risks to the health and environment of the constituents;

through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes and prohibition on open burning of solid waste; 

recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) policies and possible measures that will ensure full compliance by the barangays and its constituents on the provisions of R.A. No. 9003; and

through SWMB to fast track the processing of various requirements for the operation of a sanitary landfill in accordance with Sections 40 and 41 of R.A. No. 9003 the soonest possible time to avert adverse environmental consequences.

Based on the foregoing observations, we recommended and management agreed to the following:

The Municipal Mayor along with all the concerned officials and employees strictly follow the provisions of DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-1 in planning the programs/projects/activities funded by the 20% DF and their implementation. See to it that the schedule of implementation as planned in the APP is strictly observed and those development projects identified in the AIP are fully implemented for the benefit of the constituents;



The BAC furnish the Audit Team with the copy of the Contract of Agreement and its attachments within five (5) working days from the execution of the contract as required under Section 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 23, 2009; 



The Municipal Accountant (i) ensure that supporting documents are thoroughly checked as to accuracy and completeness before processing claims pursuant to Section 474 b(5) of R.A. No. 7160; and (ii) submit the lacking documents mentioned above for verification; and

The Municipal Engineer ensure that pictures of the progress accomplishments are properly labeled and the information provided in the billboard of projects are complete and accurate pursuant to the requirements of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013.

