We recommended and management promised to comply with the following:

The Municipal Mayor along with all the concerned officials and employees strictly follow the provisions of DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-1 in planning the programs/projects/activities funded by 20% DF and their implementation. See to it that the schedule of implementation as planned in the APP is strictly observed and those development projects identified in the AIP are fully implemented for the benefit of the constituents;

instruct the BAC to i) furnish the Audit Team with the copy of the Contract of Agreement and its attachments within five (5) working days from the execution of the contract as required under Section 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 23, 2009; ii) strengthen internal control over the post-qualification of bidders to ensure completeness and veracity of the post-qualified documents as reported in the Post- Qualification Evaluation Reports; and iii) ensure proper compliance with the requirements prescribed under the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to prevent the same lapses in future procurements;

The Municipal Accountant i) ensure that supporting documents are thoroughly checked as to accuracy and completeness before processing claims; and ii)submit the lacking documents mentioned above for verification; and

The Municipal Engineer i) be guided by the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013 in the information and publicity on programs/projects/activities of the municipality; and ii) ensure that pictures pertaining to progress accomplishments are properly labeled and dated.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

instruct the LDRRMO to prepare and submit the LDRRMFIP and Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRM to the Audit Team in accordance with Items 5.1.2 and 5.1.5 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012; 

instruct the LDRRMO and Municipal Accountant to include all the expenditures actually incurred during the year in the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRM;

instruct the LDRRMO to refrain from incurring and charging expenses not related to disaster risk reduction and management activities against the DRRM fund; and

instruct the Municipal Accountant to scrutinize the attachments to disbursement vouchers and ensure that they are complete and accurate and be guided by COA Circular No. 2015-009 in the proper recording of transactions.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor:

a. as the Local Chief Executive, should have the political will to strictly implement its solid waste management plan; 

b. through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes and prohibition on open burning of solid waste; 

c. through SWMB, comply with the requirements of the law on (a) waste segregation by placing trash bins with proper labels; (b) waste collection by ensuring that solid waste equipment like dumptrucks are operational;

d. take appropriate action on reactivation/reestablishment of the MRF and provide necessary support to barangays who have not yet establish their own MRF;

e. recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) policies and possible measures that will ensure full compliance by the barangays and its constituents on the provisions of R.A. No. 9003; and

f. through SWMB to fast track the processing of various requirements for the operation of a sanitary landfill in accordance with Sections 40 and 41 of R.A. No. 9003 the soonest possible time to avert adverse environmental consequences.

We recommended the following:

The Municipal Mayor see to it that development projects identified in the AIP were fully implemented for the benefit of the constituents;

The Municipal Accountant ensure that each transaction is supported with complete documentation and properly classified to the appropriate accounts as required by Section 4 (6) of PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 2012-001 and COA Circular No. 2015-009, respectively; 

The Municipal Engineer be guided by the provisions of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013 in the information and publicity on programs/projects/activities of the municipality;

The concerned municipal employees prepare documents/reports with extra care to avoid errors or mistakes; and 

The Municipal Accountant submit the lacking documents enumerated above.

In the light of the observations noted, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

take appropriate action regarding the non-completion of the project within the target completion date and ensure awareness of the provisions of the Memorandum of Agreement being entered into;

direct the Municipal Engineer to submit immediately the result of clarification made with the DILG – Regional Office regarding the conflict in the target barangays or any valid document showing that Barangay Lawan is one of the target barangay beneficiaries of the project and justification as to why the project was concentrated in Barangay Lawan only considering that there are still other barangays that were identified as beneficiaries, otherwise, the contract entered into with E.M. Paule Construction & Trading for the Improvement and Expansion of Alcantara Level III Water System will be rendered defective to its disadvantage;

instruct the Municipal Engineer to ensure that detailed engineering for the procurement of infrastructure projects are sufficiently carried to prevent delays in the completion of projects;

instruct the Bids and Awards Committee to strictly comply with all the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and other pertinent laws, rules and regulations on procurement; and

instruct the Municipal Accountant, being the internal auditor, to thoroughly check the documents before processing payment.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor:

require the strict and uniform implementation of the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002 on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances to all officials and employees of the municipality;

require all accountable officers and employees to settle/liquidate all their outstanding cash advances by sending confirmation, notification or demand letters. For unliquidated cash advances which are non-moving for more than 10 years, exhaust all remedies to collect or demand to liquidate the unliquidated cash advances, otherwise apply for write off in accordance with the guidelines and procedures prescribed by COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 29, 2016;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to properly classify each cash advance transaction in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-009 and reclassify the balance of Advances to Officers and Employees pertaining to the cash advances of accountable officers who are already not in the service, retired or dead amounting to P93,311.09; and

refer to COA Circular No. 2016-005 which prescribes the Guidelines and Procedures on the Write-off of Dormant Receivable Accounts, Unliquidated Cash Advances, and Fund Transfers of National Government Agencies (NGAs), Local Government Units (LGUs) and Government-Owned and Controlled Corporations (GOCCs.

